<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Bearer-Contact Press" class="currentChild" href="Bearer-Contact_Press">Bearer-Contact Press</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A type of printing press used in <a title="Offset Lithography" href="Offset_Lithography">offset lithography</a> in which the blanket and plate cylinder <a title="Bearer" href="Bearer">bearer</a>s (metal rings located at each end of each cylinder body, with diameters greater than the diameter of the cylinder body) are in tight contact with each other while the press is in operation. Such presses reduce gear wear, as the pressure of the cylinders falls on the bearers rather than the gears. Proper cylinder setting and <a title="Packing" href="Packing">packing</a> considerations vary between bearer-contact presses and <a title="Non-Bearer-Contact Press" href="Non-Bearer-Contact_Press">non-bearer-contact press</a>es. See <a title="Bearer" href="Bearer">Bearer</a>, <a title="Plate Cylinder" href="Plate_Cylinder">Plate Cylinder</a>, <a title="Blanket Cylinder" href="Blanket_Cylinder">Blanket Cylinder</a>, and <a title="Packing" href="Packing">Packing</a>. 
</p>
